  "text": "The ext_authz filter in Envoy (v1.31.2) implements external authorization with bypass and passthrough logic across multiple components:\n\n## HTTP Filter Implementation\n\nThe HTTP ext_authz filter is implemented in `source/extensions/filters/http/ext_authz/`. The main filter logic resides in `ext_authz.cc` with configuration defined in `ext_authz.h`.\n\n### Per-Route Bypass Configuration\nThe `FilterConfigPerRoute` class (ext_authz.h:231-273) enables per-route bypass configuration through the `disabled_` flag. This allows operators to selectively disable ext_authz checks on specific routes, virtual hosts, or weighted clusters. In `ext_authz.cc:810-827`, the `Filter::getPerRouteFlags()` function retrieves the most specific per-route configuration, which includes the `skip_check_` flag that determines whether authorization should be skipped.\n\nThe per-route configuration is created in `config.cc:72-77` via `ExtAuthzFilterConfig::createRouteSpecificFilterConfigTyped()`, which instantiates `FilterConfigPerRoute` from the protobuf configuration.\n\n### Authorization Check Initiation and Bypass\nIn `ext_authz.cc:226-277`, the `Filter::decodeHeaders()` function performs the main bypass logic:\n1. Line 229: Sets `skip_check_` from per-route flags\n2. Line 230-232: Early return bypassing authorization if the check is disabled\n3. Line 234-247: Checks if the filter is enabled via metadata matchers or runtime flags, allowing bypass based on filter_enabled or deny_at_disable configurations\n4. Line 251-270: Handles request body buffering configuration per-route\n5. Line 273: Initiates authorization call via `initiateCall()`\n\n### Immediate Response Path (Denial)\nThe immediate response mechanism is implemented in `ext_authz.cc:403-770` via the `Filter::onComplete()` function, which handles the authorization service response:\n1. Lines 678-736: On `CheckStatus::Denied`, sends a local reply with `sendLocalReply()` (line 717), returning status code and body from the auth service\n2. Lines 737-769: On `CheckStatus::Error`, performs failure mode analysis - either denies (line 762) or allows (line 747) based on `failure_mode_allow_` configuration\n3. Lines 432-676: On `CheckStatus::OK`, applies header mutations and stores response headers for modification (lines 559-623)\n\n### Route Cache Clearing and Header Mutation\nIn `ext_authz.cc:436-441`, when authorization succeeds and headers are modified, the route cache is cleared if configured, allowing the authorization response to influence routing decisions. This implements passthrough with modified request state.\n\n## Network Filter Implementation\n\nThe network-layer ext_authz filter in `source/extensions/filters/network/ext_authz/` provides similar authorization at the TCP connection level.\n\nIn `ext_authz.cc:40-53`, the `Filter::onData()` function:\n1. Checks if the filter is enabled via metadata matching (line 41)\n2. Defers the actual check to the first data arrival (line 49), allowing sufficient context\n3. Returns `Continue` or `StopIteration` based on authorization state\n\nThe `Filter::onComplete()` function (lines 72-130) handles authorization responses:\n1. Lines 105-115: Closes the connection on deny or non-recoverable errors\n2. Lines 119-123: Implements failure mode allowing passthrough on error with stats tracking\n3. Lines 118, 127: Sets filter return status and continues reading\n\n## Common Components\n\n### Response Handling\nThe `Response` struct (source/extensions/filters/common/ext_authz/ext_authz.h:86-129) encapsulates authorization decisions with header and query parameter mutations. This supports the passthrough path where headers are modified but traffic is allowed.\n\n### Client Implementations\nBoth `RawHttpClientImpl` (ext_authz_http_impl.h) and `GrpcClientImpl` (ext_authz_grpc_impl.h) implement the `Client` interface for communicating with authorization services. The HTTP implementation supports path prefix configuration (ext_authz_http_impl.h:39), while both support header filtering and dynamic metadata ingestion.\n\n### Check Request Creation\nThe `CheckRequestUtils` class (check_request_utils.h and check_request_utils.cc) creates authorization requests, populating request context from HTTP headers, connection info, and metadata. This enables authorization services to make decisions based on comprehensive request context.\n\n## Configuration Structure\n\nThe `FilterConfig` class (ext_authz.h:57-223) holds global configuration including:\n- `failure_mode_allow_` (line 69): Enables passthrough on auth service errors\n- `clear_route_cache_` (line 73): Controls route cache invalidation after auth response\n- Filter enabled/disabled state via runtime and metadata matchers\n- Deny-at-disable configuration for treating filter disablement as denial\n\n## Key Control Flow\n\nFor HTTP requests:\n1. Decode phase checks per-route configuration and filter enabled state\n2. If enabled, buffers request and initiates authorization check\n3. On completion, either:\n   - Sends local reply (deny)\n   - Modifies headers and continues (ok with mutations)\n   - Allows passthrough (ok)\n   - Allows passthrough on error (failure_mode_allow)\n\nFor network connections:\n1. Connection established, waits for first data\n2. Initiates authorization check\n3. Either closes connection (deny/error) or continues reading (allow/failure_mode_allow)"
}

